WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.030 --> 00:00:04.970
&gt;&gt; From the Library of
Congress in Washington DC.

00:00:20.460 --> 00:00:25.010
&gt;&gt; Well, I've said this 21 times
before so, ladies and gentlemen,

00:00:25.010 --> 00:00:29.780
welcome to the 22nd annual
Vardanants Day Lecture Series,

00:00:29.780 --> 00:00:31.730
Armenian Lecture Series.

00:00:31.730 --> 00:00:34.170
This year -- well,
they're all been special

00:00:34.170 --> 00:00:38.720
but this year is really special
because we have a conference

00:00:38.720 --> 00:00:44.140
with some of my friends,
colleagues and academic types

00:00:44.140 --> 00:00:49.920
to fill your day talking about
Armenian history and culture.

00:00:49.920 --> 00:00:54.440
But before I began, and
before we start this program,

00:00:54.440 --> 00:00:59.110
I'd like to introduce you
to a colleague of many years

00:00:59.110 --> 00:01:02.780
who has held many, various
positions at the Library

00:01:02.780 --> 00:01:06.590
of Congress, of importance
to the collections

00:01:06.590 --> 00:01:10.060
and the preservation of those
collections, and I'm delighted

00:01:10.060 --> 00:01:14.960
to introduce him thanks to the
appointment by the new librarian

00:01:14.960 --> 00:01:18.110
of Congress Dr. Carla Hayden,
I'd like to introduce you

00:01:18.110 --> 00:01:23.220
to Mr. Mark Sweeney, who is now
the principal deputy librarian

00:01:23.220 --> 00:01:25.020
of Congress.

00:01:25.020 --> 00:02:31.070
[ Applause ]

00:02:31.070 --> 00:02:32.370
&gt;&gt; Thank You, Lee.

00:02:32.370 --> 00:02:36.540
Ladies and gentlemen, welcome
to the Library of Congress

00:02:36.540 --> 00:02:40.880
in today's 22nd Vardanants
Day, Armenian Lecture Series.

00:02:40.880 --> 00:02:43.710
I'm delighted to be
addressing you in this hall

00:02:43.710 --> 00:02:48.030
in the historic Thomas Jefferson
Building, attached to a room

00:02:48.030 --> 00:02:50.070
on there that is dedicated to
Woodrow Wilson, the president

00:02:50.070 --> 00:02:53.250
of so many important
moments in history,

00:02:53.250 --> 00:02:54.910
especially of the Armenians

00:02:54.910 --> 00:02:57.510
in the early part
of the 20th century.

00:02:57.510 --> 00:03:00.290
In 1991m Mrs. Marjorie Dadian
made a generous donation

00:03:00.290 --> 00:03:01.790
to the Near East Section in
the name of our husband Arthur,

00:03:01.790 --> 00:03:03.320
for the health and maintenance
of the Armenian collections.

00:03:03.320 --> 00:03:04.620
That gift not only allowed us

00:03:04.620 --> 00:03:05.920
to appoint the first
Armenian area specialists,

00:03:05.920 --> 00:03:07.220
but also was the
genesis of a long-running

00:03:07.220 --> 00:03:08.600
and very successful olestra
series, which began in 1994,

00:03:08.600 --> 00:03:09.900
which is why we're here today.

00:03:09.900 --> 00:03:11.200
Since that time, the Armenian
collections have grown

00:03:11.200 --> 00:03:12.500
from some 7,000 items
to over 40,000 --

00:03:12.500 --> 00:03:13.800
45,000 items in our collection.

00:03:13.800 --> 00:03:15.100
The Near East section has
sponsored conferences,

00:03:15.100 --> 00:03:16.400
such as the American response to
the Armenian Genocide in 2000,

00:03:16.400 --> 00:03:18.530
a major exhibit in 2012 to
celebrate the 500th anniversary

00:03:18.530 --> 00:03:19.830
of the first printed
Armenian book.

00:03:19.830 --> 00:03:21.130
That exhibit to note wisdom

00:03:21.130 --> 00:03:22.430
and instruction the
Armenian literary tradition

00:03:22.430 --> 00:03:23.730
at the Library of Congress,
brought nearly a quarter

00:03:23.730 --> 00:03:25.030
of a million visitors here to
the library into the galleries.

00:03:25.030 --> 00:03:26.330
The Library of Congress
remains an described important

00:03:26.330 --> 00:03:27.630
repository of the
world's heritage,

00:03:27.630 --> 00:03:28.930
this universal collection.

00:03:28.930 --> 00:03:30.230
And we're proud to include
among those ancient,

00:03:30.230 --> 00:03:31.530
yet still vibrant cultures, the
history of the Armenian people,

00:03:31.530 --> 00:03:32.830
as exemplified in the talks

00:03:32.830 --> 00:03:34.130
of the scholars you will
soon hear today and enjoy.

00:03:34.130 --> 00:03:35.430
Again, welcome to the
Library of Congress

00:03:35.430 --> 00:03:36.730
and please enjoy
today's program.

00:03:36.730 --> 00:03:38.040
Thank you very much.

00:03:38.040 --> 00:03:40.040
[ Applause ]

00:03:40.040 --> 00:03:42.160
&gt;&gt; Thank you, Mark Sweeney.

00:03:42.160 --> 00:03:46.420
None of these programs
have happened in a vacuum.

00:03:46.420 --> 00:03:51.670
We have many people who are
responsible for supporting,

00:03:51.670 --> 00:03:56.180
for helping erect everything
that in the construction

00:03:56.180 --> 00:04:00.830
of lectures and exhibits, some
of whom I will mention later.

00:04:00.830 --> 00:04:04.750
But at this point the most
important is the next speaker,

00:04:04.750 --> 00:04:07.420
Dr. Mary-Jane Deeb who is
the chief of the African

00:04:07.420 --> 00:04:10.410
and Middle Eastern Division who
has been a constant supporter

00:04:10.410 --> 00:04:13.780
