I'll speak for about an hour is

00:10:25.500 --> 00:10:27.970
that -- no [laughter].

00:10:27.970 --> 00:10:29.660
No? OK, fine.

00:10:29.660 --> 00:10:34.020
Let me tell you the
genesis of this conference.

00:10:34.020 --> 00:10:37.540
A little over a year ago I
was approached by someone

00:10:37.540 --> 00:10:40.200
from the Smithsonian
and said, "this festival

00:10:40.200 --> 00:10:43.540
on Armenian culture is
happening, would the library

00:10:43.540 --> 00:10:46.700
like to do something to
complement this festival?"

00:10:46.700 --> 00:10:48.250
And I said, "absolutely".

00:10:48.250 --> 00:10:51.360
And I said, "now,
what could I do?"

00:10:51.360 --> 00:10:56.440
Now, I had been wanting to
invite Dr. Armen Matterosian

00:10:56.440 --> 00:11:02.250
and Dr. Luke Vartan Baronian to
participate in the conference

00:11:02.250 --> 00:11:07.000
because of their work on
R2 and genetics etcetera,

00:11:07.000 --> 00:11:09.820
and I built this
conference around them.

00:11:09.820 --> 00:11:14.360
And I must tell, you I invited
these dear people and not one

00:11:14.360 --> 00:11:16.850
of them took more than
24 hours to say, "yes,

00:11:16.850 --> 00:11:18.560
we would like to participate".

00:11:18.560 --> 00:11:21.270
However, Dr. Baronian
is not here

00:11:21.270 --> 00:11:24.640
because of an unavoidable
emergency

00:11:24.640 --> 00:11:28.800
and Armen has told me he
did not plan it this way,

00:11:28.800 --> 00:11:32.300
but his wife was due
yesterday so, I said,

00:11:32.300 --> 00:11:35.050
"you're forgiven
for not attending".

00:11:36.070 --> 00:11:40.070
This year marks the 50th
anniversary of my beginning

00:11:40.070 --> 00:11:45.390
to study Armenian history
and culture, academically.

00:11:45.390 --> 00:11:52.140
I take this study so seriously
that I will no longer call it

00:11:52.140 --> 00:11:55.190
"Armenian Studies",
because that reduces it

00:11:55.190 --> 00:12:00.520
to almost a ghetto studying of
Armenian history and culture.

00:12:00.520 --> 00:12:06.210
This is the scholarly study
of Armenia, including history,

00:12:06.210 --> 00:12:09.340
linguistics, literature.

00:12:09.340 --> 00:12:13.180
One of the things that is
maddening that I find --

00:12:13.180 --> 00:12:16.690
with every culture, but
Armenian in particular,

00:12:16.690 --> 00:12:18.950
is the fact that there
are certain tropes

00:12:18.950 --> 00:12:21.460
that everyone knows.

00:12:21.460 --> 00:12:25.660
You know, the ark
landed on Mount Ararat,

00:12:25.660 --> 00:12:30.850
Armenia as first Christian
country, the genocide,

00:12:30.850 --> 00:12:33.560
the kingdom of Silesia.

00:12:33.560 --> 00:12:36.520
People know this, but
what they don't know is

00:12:36.520 --> 00:12:39.770
from the very first
solid mention of Armenia

00:12:39.770 --> 00:12:43.420
in the 6th century BC by the
Greek geographer Heckatias

00:12:43.420 --> 00:12:46.070
of Mialitus and on a
Persian inscription

00:12:46.070 --> 00:12:48.960
of Darrius the Great,
from that time

00:12:48.960 --> 00:12:51.700
to the present there
is an exceedingly rich

00:12:51.700 --> 00:12:54.880
and largely unknown history.

00:12:54.880 --> 00:12:58.470
So, I said -- I wrote to
my dear friends and said,

00:12:58.470 --> 00:13:02.530
"I would like anything but first
Christian country, genocide

00:13:02.530 --> 00:13:05.990
and the ark landing
on Mount Ararat".

00:13:05.990 --> 00:13:07.290
If everyone had been able

00:13:07.290 --> 00:13:10.320
to come you literally would
have gone away at 5 o'clock,

00:13:10.320 --> 00:13:13.900
totally confused because you
would have been bombarded

00:13:13.900 --> 00:13:18.010
with fact after fact and
richness after richness.

00:13:18.010 --> 00:13:20.580
You still are going to
go away not confused,

00:13:20.580 --> 00:13:24.420
but very enlightened about
this very rich history.

00:13:24.420 --> 00:13:27.690
I'm just going to say two things
that you need to both know

00:13:27.690 --> 00:13:30.770
about Armenia before
we continue.

00:13:30.770 --> 00:13:34.000
Look at the map.

00:13:34.000 --> 00:13:37.380
You will see that Armenia
historically has been

00:13:37.380 --> 00:13:41.430
in eastern Anatolia,
the Armenian plateau

00:13:41.430 --> 00:13:43.320
and up to the Caucasus.

00:13:43.320 --> 00:13:48.120
East-west transit,
very easy, north-south,

00:13:48.120 --> 00:13:51.390
transit extremely difficult.

00:13:51.390 --> 00:13:54.560
So, and this is known
as Garzonian's law

00:13:54.560 --> 00:13:58.280
after Nina Garzon at
Columbia University.

00:13:58.280 --> 00:14:00.920
When the surrounding powers --

00:14:00.920 --> 00:14:03.030
because Armenia was
always a client state

00:14:03.030 --> 00:14:07.340
between surrounding powers,
were equal in strength or equal

00:14:07.340 --> 00:14:10.670
in weakness, Armenia flourished

00:14:10.670 --> 00:14:14.940
because east-west trade
transit was plentiful.

00:14:14.940 --> 00:14:21.230
When, however, one of those
entities grew stronger,

00:14:21.230 --> 00:14:25.930
it created a vacuum, sucking the
other power into guess where?

00:14:25.930 --> 00:14:28.550
Armenia, and it was
at these periods

00:14:28.550 --> 00:14:32.340
that Armenia did not thrive.

00:14:32.340 --> 00:14:36.320
That is a constant in Armenian
history, most of the time it was

00:14:36.320 --> 00:14:38.700
to surrounding powers -- I
could argue now but I won't,

00:14:38.700 --> 00:14:41.080
that we have five at the moment.

00:14:41.080 --> 00:14:46.280
So, and the other constant is
the fact that Armenia thrived

00:14:46.280 --> 00:14:49.180
and survived because there
were communities on top

00:14:49.180 --> 00:14:52.250
of many different
mountains, and when one fell,

00:14:52.250 --> 00:14:54.440
the other one existed.

00:14:54.440 --> 00:15:00.780
This fostered independence
but it also fostered a feeling

00:15:00.780 --> 00:15:04.370
against a centralized authority.

00:15:04.370 --> 00:15:06.770
Those are the two constants
of Armenian history,

00:15:06.770 --> 00:15:09.640
and within those constants,
I want you to listen

00:15:09.640 --> 00:15:11.960
to everything that follows.

00:15:11.960 --> 00:15:14.700
And what is going to
follow right now is

00:15:14.700 --> 00:15:18.760
from my dear friend Helen C.
Evans the Metropolitan Museum

00:15:18.760 --> 00:15:20.060
of Art.

00:15:20.060 --> 00:15:22.370
She is the Mary and
Michael Jahara's curator

00:15:22.370 --> 00:15:23.670
