00:16:08.610 --> 00:16:13.800
&gt;&gt; So, as the first speaker,
I would like to be the first

00:16:13.800 --> 00:16:16.980
to thank LaVon, not just
for organizing today

00:16:16.980 --> 00:16:21.120
but for all he's done farming
in studies in the United States,

00:16:21.120 --> 00:16:24.680
by what he's done at the Library
of Congress over so many years.

00:16:24.680 --> 00:16:30.420
Its effect is something that we
don't always fully think about,

00:16:30.420 --> 00:16:32.930
but we really should
always admire.

00:16:32.930 --> 00:16:36.420
So, I hope very much
that all of you join me

00:16:36.420 --> 00:16:39.460
in admiring him and
what he's done.

00:16:39.460 --> 00:16:43.400
As I hope you will know from
him, we will open an exhibition

00:16:43.400 --> 00:16:44.920
on medieval Armenian art

00:16:44.920 --> 00:16:49.130
at the MET this fall,
on September 22nd.

00:16:49.130 --> 00:16:53.900
And in our research for the
exhibition and its catalog,

00:16:53.900 --> 00:16:59.360
I and other catalog authors
have realized that our view

00:16:59.360 --> 00:17:03.210
of the role of the Mongols,
in terms of Silesia,

00:17:03.210 --> 00:17:07.400
as well as greater Armenia,
should be reconsidered.

00:17:07.400 --> 00:17:11.150
The devastation caused by
the Mongols as they advanced

00:17:11.150 --> 00:17:15.130
into greater Armenia in the
early 1200s has been described

00:17:15.130 --> 00:17:18.990
by Gregoria Wagner in Caracas
[inaudible] and recorded

00:17:18.990 --> 00:17:21.710
in numerous manuscript
color fonts.

00:17:21.710 --> 00:17:24.890
However, the exhibition's
research has shown

00:17:24.890 --> 00:17:28.070
that there was another,
more positive aspect

00:17:28.070 --> 00:17:31.830
of the interaction between
the Mongols and the Armenians

00:17:31.830 --> 00:17:37.460
in Silesia and greater Armenia
that should be studied further.

00:17:37.460 --> 00:17:41.410
That aspect is how much the
critical role Armenians played

00:17:41.410 --> 00:17:45.770
on the trade routes of the packs
Mongolica [phonetic] contributed

00:17:45.770 --> 00:17:48.340
to Armenian wealth in Silesia

00:17:48.340 --> 00:17:52.400
and greater Armenia during the
second half of the 13th century

00:17:52.400 --> 00:17:55.710
and well into the 14th century.

00:17:55.710 --> 00:17:59.490
This talk introduces the topic

00:17:59.490 --> 00:18:01.650
from an art historical
perspective,

00:18:01.650 --> 00:18:05.980
in the hope that others will
study the matter further.

00:18:05.980 --> 00:18:09.750
As someone whose primary
research has been on the kingdom

00:18:09.750 --> 00:18:14.660
of Silesia, I'm approaching the
issue through evidence there.

00:18:14.660 --> 00:18:17.260
Like others, I've
always recognized

00:18:17.260 --> 00:18:21.200
that the Silesian king had the
first alliance with the Mongols

00:18:21.200 --> 00:18:24.150
in the early 1250's
was important.

00:18:24.150 --> 00:18:27.230
However, when viewing the
handsome, fortified ruins

00:18:27.230 --> 00:18:30.020
of the Armenian killing
Kingdom of Silesia

00:18:30.020 --> 00:18:32.540
on the Mediterranean coast,

00:18:32.540 --> 00:18:36.800
I've never adequately considered
the source of the funds required

00:18:36.800 --> 00:18:41.110
to maintain such magnificent
sites as the hegemon fortress

00:18:41.110 --> 00:18:43.690
of Lambrom on the
right and the walls

00:18:43.690 --> 00:18:47.090
of the Silesian capital
of Cyss on the left.

00:18:47.090 --> 00:18:49.880
I hope to show today
that from the time this

00:18:49.880 --> 00:18:54.640
of the Silesian-Mongol
Alliance until the fall

00:18:54.640 --> 00:18:58.880
of the Silesian Kingdom
in the late 14th century,

00:18:58.880 --> 00:19:02.490
Silesian control of
Mongol trade routes was key

00:19:02.490 --> 00:19:06.880
to the great Kingdom's
wealth and authority.

00:19:06.880 --> 00:19:09.930
Richly gilded royal
portraits like these

00:19:09.930 --> 00:19:11.720
of king Heptune's son LaVon

00:19:11.720 --> 00:19:15.890
and his wife display
elaborate silk robes.

00:19:15.890 --> 00:19:21.170
What was the source of the
silks in 1262 when LaVon

00:19:21.170 --> 00:19:24.770
and lady Quran were shown if
their marriage on the left,

00:19:24.770 --> 00:19:27.210
and a decade later when
they knelt in prayer

00:19:27.210 --> 00:19:29.910
with their children
on the right?

00:19:29.910 --> 00:19:34.020
It's not enough to argue as
I long have that these images

00:19:34.020 --> 00:19:37.300
with their extensive
references to Byzantine art,

00:19:37.300 --> 00:19:40.170
were only evidence of
the increasing power

00:19:40.170 --> 00:19:42.740
of the Silesian state
and its ambition

00:19:42.740 --> 00:19:46.450
to be the new Byzantium, as the
power of the Empire weakened

00:19:46.450 --> 00:19:49.890
with the Fourth Crusade in 1204.

00:19:49.890 --> 00:19:53.150
It is relevant that they
displayed their ambition

00:19:53.150 --> 00:19:56.770
by increasingly adopting
the Royal images and dress

00:19:56.770 --> 00:19:58.530
of the Byzantine emperors.

00:19:58.530 --> 00:20:01.420
At their wedding, the young
royals are shown being blessed

00:20:01.420 --> 00:20:04.110
by Christ, as found
in Byzantine art,

00:20:04.110 --> 00:20:07.390
and Prince LaVon wears the
tablon of Byzantine Royals

00:20:07.390 --> 00:20:09.090
on his tunic -- on his mantle.

00:20:09.090 --> 00:20:14.140
A few years later, when they
kneel beneath the Byzantine

00:20:14.140 --> 00:20:18.510
douses, now king LaVon and
queen Quran, they are dressed

00:20:18.510 --> 00:20:20.170
like the Byzantine emperors,

00:20:20.170 --> 00:20:23.240
including wearing
the imperial laurels.

00:20:23.240 --> 00:20:27.720
Nothing in the images
directly relates to Mongols.

00:20:27.720 --> 00:20:32.170
Rather the only other
external influence is the West,

00:20:32.170 --> 00:20:36.430
as shown in the kneeling poses
and the crowns of the royals

00:20:36.430 --> 00:20:41.080
and the Queen Quran
Gospel on the right.

00:20:41.080 --> 00:20:44.430
What is relevant today
is to consider the source

00:20:44.430 --> 00:20:47.910
of the wealth that supported
the richly gilded portraits

00:20:47.910 --> 00:20:49.640
and the ambitions

00:20:49.640 --> 00:20:53.440
of the Silesian ruling
class they portray.

00:20:53.440 --> 00:20:56.430
I am arguing that the
answer was a control

00:20:56.430 --> 00:20:59.190
of trade routes for the Mongols.

00:20:59.190 --> 00:21:01.640
Armenians had long
been of critical force

00:21:01.640 --> 00:21:04.540
on the Silk Route
trade, east-west,

00:21:04.540 --> 00:21:07.650
as LaVon referred to
with the Garzoian.

00:21:07.650 --> 00:21:10.940
In the 13th century with
arrival the Mongols,

00:21:10.940 --> 00:21:15.080
the Armenians ultimately were
able to maintain a similar role

00:21:15.080 --> 00:21:19.610
under Mongol rule, and
expanded, by controlling Ayahs,

00:21:19.610 --> 00:21:23.350
as we will see, a major
port city for the exchange

00:21:23.350 --> 00:21:25.530
of goods with the West.

00:21:25.530 --> 00:21:27.830
The expanse of the textile trade

00:21:27.830 --> 00:21:30.970
for Silesia is most
easily visible

00:21:30.970 --> 00:21:35.370
in these two manuscripts written
for archbishop Johannes John,

00:21:35.370 --> 00:21:38.760
the brother of King Heptune The
First and uncle of King LaVon.

00:21:38.760 --> 00:21:43.260
On the left, in the
Marshall Ocean gospel of 1274

00:21:43.260 --> 00:21:44.870
from the Morgan Library,

00:21:44.870 --> 00:21:50.320
the archbishop wears a
fleur-de-lis decorated vestment

00:21:50.320 --> 00:21:54.650
and he's to the far left.

00:21:54.650 --> 00:21:57.420
That is representative
of Western Europe,

00:21:57.420 --> 00:21:59.590
most especially France.

00:21:59.590 --> 00:22:03.790
He presents the marshal's family
to the Virgin they are kneeling,

00:22:03.790 --> 00:22:07.350
and she is reaching --
extending her mantle over them.

00:22:07.350 --> 00:22:11.330
That's opposed, most closely
associated with Minnuchio's

00:22:11.330 --> 00:22:13.400
"Madonna of the Franciscans",

00:22:13.400 --> 00:22:15.800
as their necessity
unrecognized long ago.

00:22:15.800 --> 00:22:20.590
On the right in 1289,
the year of his death,

00:22:20.590 --> 00:22:25.450
the Archbishop's tunic is
decorated with a Chinese dragon.

00:22:25.450 --> 00:22:29.310
Dikron Kim Jong has linked
the Dragons posed to a textile

00:22:29.310 --> 00:22:32.460
in the MET's collection,
from East Central Asia,

00:22:32.460 --> 00:22:35.810
a region under Mongol control.

00:22:35.810 --> 00:22:39.660
You see a fleur-de-lis
textile beside the early image

00:22:39.660 --> 00:22:42.200
of the archbishop on the left,

00:22:42.200 --> 00:22:45.440
and the MET's Chinese dragon
beside his later image

00:22:45.440 --> 00:22:46.900
on the right.

00:22:46.900 --> 00:22:50.160
The fabrics of the Arts bishops
two vestments represent the

00:22:50.160 --> 00:22:53.490
extreme ends of Silesia
trade routes.

00:22:53.490 --> 00:22:56.050
To the west, links to France,

00:22:56.050 --> 00:23:00.370
whose King Louis the Ninth had
allied so closely with Silesia

00:23:00.370 --> 00:23:03.520
when he came East on
crusade, that on his return

00:23:03.520 --> 00:23:07.350
to France he left his
ward Bowman the Sixth,

00:23:07.350 --> 00:23:11.760
the young Prince of Antioch
under the care of King Heptune.

00:23:11.760 --> 00:23:15.070
To the east, a continued
Armenian presence

00:23:15.070 --> 00:23:19.210
on the silk routes that were
now under Mongol control.

00:23:19.210 --> 00:23:22.320
By the dates of bishop
John's manuscripts,

00:23:22.320 --> 00:23:26.160
the Silesian state had extensive
links with the Mongols.

00:23:26.160 --> 00:23:29.200
To avoid Mongol military
conquests that had happened

00:23:29.200 --> 00:23:32.820
in greater Armenia, King Heptune
had surrendered the harem

00:23:32.820 --> 00:23:35.290
of the Seljuk ruler,
who had been sent to him

00:23:35.290 --> 00:23:37.970
for safety to the Mongols.

00:23:37.970 --> 00:23:40.370
Constable Simbad had
to his older brother,

00:23:40.370 --> 00:23:44.040
then went to the Mongol
capital at Karakorum in Siberia

00:23:44.040 --> 00:23:48.660
and 1247-48, where he
successfully arranged the first

00:23:48.660 --> 00:23:51.670
treaty between the Mongols
and a Christian state

00:23:51.670 --> 00:23:53.900
which had not been invaded.

00:23:53.900 --> 00:23:56.430
When Simbad returned to Silesia,

00:23:56.430 --> 00:23:59.160
he brought with him
a Mongol wife,

00:23:59.160 --> 00:24:03.490
as Mongol treaties were
confirmed by marriage alliances.

00:24:03.490 --> 00:24:07.830
The son of that alliance is
recorded as being present

00:24:07.830 --> 00:24:12.300
at the Silesian court
in 1264-65,

00:24:12.300 --> 00:24:15.810
evidence of the Silesian
state's role as a vassal

00:24:15.810 --> 00:24:20.920
of the Mongols was also clear
clearly demonstrated in 1260,

00:24:20.920 --> 00:24:25.510
when King Heptune, accompanied
by the Prince of Antioch,

00:24:25.510 --> 00:24:29.000
marched with the Mongols as
they entered Damascus upon their

00:24:29.000 --> 00:24:30.380
conquest of the city.

00:24:30.380 --> 00:24:35.990
Silesia's port cities,
especially Ayahs,

00:24:35.990 --> 00:24:40.470
are an understudied link in
the appreciation of the wealth

00:24:40.470 --> 00:24:44.510
that came to Silesia through
control of Mongol trade routes.

00:24:44.510 --> 00:24:49.780
The Western book of
Marbles illuminated in 1271,

00:24:49.780 --> 00:24:52.500
shows Ayahs as a busy
city, filled with men

00:24:52.500 --> 00:24:55.290
and Western dress as
you see on the left.

00:24:55.290 --> 00:24:58.480
But it was a Silesian
city, and by that fact,

00:24:58.480 --> 00:25:02.240
the westernmost port
of the Mongol Empire.

00:25:02.240 --> 00:25:07.330
Western Europeans who wish
to reach the east for trade,

00:25:07.330 --> 00:25:09.870
or as missionaries,
were most likely

00:25:09.870 --> 00:25:12.920
to enter the east through Ayahs.

00:25:12.920 --> 00:25:16.530
Most famous of those was
Marco Polo, who went east

00:25:16.530 --> 00:25:19.580
through the port in 1271.

00:25:19.580 --> 00:25:23.890
He recorded that it was a city
full of spices and textiles

00:25:23.890 --> 00:25:28.200
of wool and cloth of gold, that
were brought there from inland,

00:25:28.200 --> 00:25:31.050
clearly meaning that these
goods were then transported

00:25:31.050 --> 00:25:32.630
further west.

00:25:32.630 --> 00:25:35.740
The image on the screen
doesn't record in a way

00:25:35.740 --> 00:25:39.740
that we can recognize the
Silesians who rule the city,

00:25:39.740 --> 00:25:41.880
are any Mongols who would
have been interested

00:25:41.880 --> 00:25:44.390
in protecting their
Western north city,

00:25:44.390 --> 00:25:46.310
yet they were present.

00:25:46.310 --> 00:25:49.350
And this is shown on a portalon,

00:25:49.350 --> 00:25:55.590
a chart of the Mediterranean
Sea routes of 1339 on the right.

00:25:55.590 --> 00:25:57.790
Let's see if I can
make this work.

00:25:57.790 --> 00:26:01.110
Silesia -- boy, that's
doing no good.

00:26:01.110 --> 00:26:05.340
So, come two-thirds of the
way down and third of the way

00:26:05.340 --> 00:26:08.780
over you see kind
of a green square,

00:26:08.780 --> 00:26:12.520
that is Silesia and
it's port cities.

00:26:12.520 --> 00:26:17.790
The Silesian flags in this
western map are prominently

00:26:17.790 --> 00:26:21.990
displayed and Eius and the
other solution ports of Tarsus

00:26:21.990 --> 00:26:24.490
and Cortez are clearly
identified

00:26:24.490 --> 00:26:27.750
within the green area, if
you can see it clearly.

00:26:27.750 --> 00:26:31.840
What's also interesting is
that the two mount peaks

00:26:31.840 --> 00:26:36.520
of Mount Ararat are, if you go
up, and there's a red square

00:26:36.520 --> 00:26:38.720
and then right to the side
of that are two green Peaks,

00:26:38.720 --> 00:26:40.440
which actually have
Noah's Arc on them,

00:26:40.440 --> 00:26:43.450
and are clearly identified
as Mount Ararat.

00:26:43.450 --> 00:26:46.670
And I think -- I would suggest
that that shows that they know

00:26:46.670 --> 00:26:50.340
that goods are traveling through
greater Armenia to reach Silesia

00:26:50.340 --> 00:26:54.220
to be loaded onto the ships
whose roots are being shown

00:26:54.220 --> 00:26:55.520
on this map.

00:26:55.520 --> 00:26:59.530
And that this is
a relevant aspect

00:26:59.530 --> 00:27:02.710
of what makes Silesia
so wealthy.

00:27:06.040 --> 00:27:11.000
Mongol Authority and Silesia in
the early 1300s is most visible

00:27:11.000 --> 00:27:13.810
and the illumination of
king LaVon the fourth

00:27:13.810 --> 00:27:18.160
by Sergei's pit sack of 1331.

00:27:18.160 --> 00:27:22.060
The text is a translation
of a crusader legal code,

00:27:22.060 --> 00:27:27.780
the ascesis of Antioch meant for
use in Silesia, and King LaVon

00:27:27.780 --> 00:27:31.280
on the upper right wears
a western fleur-de-lis

00:27:31.280 --> 00:27:33.220
inspired crown.

00:27:33.220 --> 00:27:38.330
However, he sits cross-legged on
a low throne, the type of pose

00:27:38.330 --> 00:27:42.990
and throne found in depictions
of Mongol authorities.

00:27:42.990 --> 00:27:46.090
By this date, the Western
presence through intermarriage

00:27:46.090 --> 00:27:49.000
and connections with the
Catholic Franciscans was

00:27:49.000 --> 00:27:52.640
so widespread in Silesia that it
would seem logical for the King

00:27:52.640 --> 00:27:55.920
to be shown sitting,
as in the West.

00:27:55.920 --> 00:27:58.360
And I would argue
that his Eastern pose

00:27:58.360 --> 00:28:01.870
in this image should be
understood as further evidence

00:28:01.870 --> 00:28:04.000
of the important of
Silesia relations

00:28:04.000 --> 00:28:07.690
with their Mongol overlords,
whom we know had troops

00:28:07.690 --> 00:28:12.000
in Silesia that often
functioned his tax collectors.

00:28:12.000 --> 00:28:15.060
Silesian's links with the
Mongols have been have --

00:28:15.060 --> 00:28:17.650
excuse me, Silesian links

00:28:17.650 --> 00:28:19.890
with the Mongols must
have included connections

00:28:19.890 --> 00:28:21.870
with the trade routes
the Armenians

00:28:21.870 --> 00:28:25.850
of Greater Armenia controlled
for the Mongols also.

00:28:25.850 --> 00:28:29.240
Rachel Kashkarian and the
exhibition catalogue notes

00:28:29.240 --> 00:28:31.890
that the authority
of Silesia was such,

00:28:31.890 --> 00:28:35.580
that around 1200 Anni
refused to make changes

00:28:35.580 --> 00:28:39.000
in religious practices without
the approval of the King

00:28:39.000 --> 00:28:42.370
of Silesia and the
patriarch of Romkla.

00:28:42.370 --> 00:28:44.300
Evidence of continuing
connections

00:28:44.300 --> 00:28:45.810
between Greater Armenia arsal

00:28:45.810 --> 00:28:48.910
and Silesia are also
found in manuscripts.

00:28:48.910 --> 00:28:52.870
A colophon and a
commentary on Isaiah records

00:28:52.870 --> 00:28:56.200
that it was written
in Silesia in 1295 --

00:28:56.200 --> 00:29:00.280
1299 before being sent to
the monastery of Gladsor,

00:29:00.280 --> 00:29:03.160
whose school was called
a "Second Athens".

00:29:03.160 --> 00:29:06.270
The portrait of S.A
Negetski on the right,

00:29:06.270 --> 00:29:09.760
he's at the upper left
who was its great teacher,

00:29:09.760 --> 00:29:12.760
was added to the
work at Gladsor.

00:29:12.760 --> 00:29:15.930
Wealthy Armenian families,
especially the Prussians

00:29:15.930 --> 00:29:18.950
and Arabellians funded
the school.

00:29:21.320 --> 00:29:24.200
This is the era when
the Persians, Karyans

00:29:24.200 --> 00:29:26.850
and Orbellians flourished
through their control

00:29:26.850 --> 00:29:29.250
of trade routes for the Mongols.

00:29:29.250 --> 00:29:31.810
Through greater Armenia
and perhaps beyond,

00:29:31.810 --> 00:29:35.050
our historical evidence of
the wealth of the Persians

00:29:35.050 --> 00:29:38.470
and the exhibition includes
this handsome reliquary

00:29:38.470 --> 00:29:44.310
of the true cross on the left
that Prince Asayah dedicated

00:29:44.310 --> 00:29:48.170
to a monastery of vegetarians,
providing perpetual problems

00:29:48.170 --> 00:29:51.950
with what to call it, his
portrait is at the base.

00:29:51.950 --> 00:29:58.220
You see it in detail that I
blew up, with his hands raised

00:29:58.220 --> 00:30:00.130
in prayer in the
ancient Christian manner.

00:30:00.130 --> 00:30:05.450
His son, Emir Hassan,
completed the monastery

00:30:05.450 --> 00:30:09.550
"The White Virgin" begun by his
father that is at the top right,

00:30:09.550 --> 00:30:12.280
and decorated it with an
image of himself hunting

00:30:12.280 --> 00:30:15.750
in Mongol dress, that
you see below it.

00:30:15.750 --> 00:30:18.750
I would suggest that the
Mongol features on both

00:30:18.750 --> 00:30:22.740
of these men may
indicate that the family,

00:30:22.740 --> 00:30:27.060
like Constable Simbad in Silesia
seam it at their authority

00:30:27.060 --> 00:30:30.880
with the Mongols by the
necessary intermarriage

00:30:30.880 --> 00:30:32.690
with the elite, because
it was the way

00:30:32.690 --> 00:30:34.530
on treaties were concluded.

00:30:34.530 --> 00:30:39.100
And to conclude, I
am going to be brief.

00:30:39.100 --> 00:30:43.090
I believe that further study
is needed of the relations

00:30:43.090 --> 00:30:45.410
between the Mongols
and Armenians

00:30:45.410 --> 00:30:48.260
of Silesia and greater Armenia.

00:30:48.260 --> 00:30:53.160
This nativity scene of 1311
has long been considered

00:30:53.160 --> 00:30:56.820
to be a work created in
the Mongol capital Tabriz.

00:30:56.820 --> 00:31:00.760
Silvie Marion, who is speaking
today, as shown in the catalogue

00:31:00.760 --> 00:31:03.530
for Armenia, that it was
produced at Glandsor,

00:31:03.530 --> 00:31:09.540
but in 1311 when the monastery
was in contact with Silesia.

00:31:09.540 --> 00:31:11.860
And Evalion suggests
in the catalogue

00:31:11.860 --> 00:31:13.920
that the Nativity displays the

00:31:13.920 --> 00:31:16.750
"may chi" [phonetic]
in Mongol dress.

00:31:16.750 --> 00:31:21.420
If so, it may be that by
the early 14th century,

00:31:21.420 --> 00:31:23.090
Armenians profiting

00:31:23.090 --> 00:31:26.770
by controlling Mongol trade
routes solve the Mongols

00:31:26.770 --> 00:31:33.150
to their east, and as positive
a light as this image suggests.

00:31:33.150 --> 00:31:36.970
As research expands on the work
done in the exhibition catalogue

00:31:36.970 --> 00:31:41.590
by a variety of authors, with
most especially Rachel Costaryan

00:31:41.590 --> 00:31:44.880
on the Armenian wealth,
derived from being a power

00:31:44.880 --> 00:31:49.350
on Mongol trade routes, I
think other issues will arise.

00:31:49.350 --> 00:31:53.830
And one of interest to me is
whether the Silesian Armenians,

00:31:53.830 --> 00:31:58.660
who moved to the Crimea,
which was under Mongol,

00:31:58.660 --> 00:32:02.520
rule as the Mongols
devastated their own country,

00:32:02.520 --> 00:32:04.720
move there as a deliberate
choice

00:32:04.720 --> 00:32:07.730
to maintain their trade
routes with the Mongols,

00:32:07.730 --> 00:32:12.030
even as the extent of the
"Pox Mongolica" declined.

00:32:12.030 --> 00:32:15.130
I hope this brief
introduction to the question

00:32:15.130 --> 00:32:18.040
of the Mongol impact of
the wealth of Silesia

00:32:18.040 --> 00:32:19.340
and Mongol great control

00:32:19.340 --> 00:32:22.430
of Greater Armenia will
encourage further research

00:32:22.430 --> 00:32:25.230
into the role of the
Armenians as a power

00:32:25.230 --> 00:32:26.530
on Mongol trade routes.

00:32:26.530 --> 00:32:28.330
Thank you.

00:32:28.330 --> 00:32:34.800
[ Applause ]

00:32:34.800 --> 00:32:36.210
&gt;&gt; Thank You, Dr. Evans, I think

00:32:36.210 --> 00:32:40.360
that actually is a brilliant
introduction to what I said

00:32:40.360 --> 00:32:42.560
that there's so much
left to be studied

00:32:42.560 --> 00:32:44.290
and produced in Armenian
history.

00:32:44.290 --> 00:32:49.640
Our next speaker is someone who
is not unknown to the Library

00:32:49.640 --> 00:32:53.310
of Congress and to the
region, Dr. Amy Landau.

00:32:53.310 --> 00:32:56.860
She is at the -- she is the
director of cultural affairs

00:32:56.860 --> 00:33:01.000
and curator of Islamic and
South and Southeast Asian art

00:33:01.000 --> 00:33:04.080
at the Walters Art
Museum in Baltimore.

00:33:04.080 --> 00:33:07.390
And if you have not been
there I really urge you to go

00:33:07.390 --> 00:33:11.270
to see the splendors, and not
just the Armenians splendors.

00:33:11.270 --> 00:33:15.020
Dr. Landau will speak on
a concert of luxury wares

00:33:15.020 --> 00:33:16.320
and estates, the will

00:33:16.320 --> 00:33:19.090
of the 17th century
Armenian merchants Po-hos

00:33:19.090 --> 00:33:21.510
[inaudible] Anyang.

00:33:21.510 --> 00:33:26.580
[ Applause ]

00:33:26.580 --> 00:33:27.880
&gt;&gt; Thank you.

00:33:27.880 --> 00:33:29.180
Can you all hear me?

00:33:29.180 --> 00:33:33.890
I would like to begin by
warmly thanking LaVon to return

00:33:33.890 --> 00:33:37.990
to some old friends who I'll
talk about today, and also to be

00:33:37.990 --> 00:33:40.810
in the company of good friends.

00:33:40.810 --> 00:33:44.190
And I hope to welcome all of
you to the Walters Art Museum,

00:33:44.190 --> 00:33:47.080
it's only 45 minutes away.

00:33:47.080 --> 00:33:50.840
We honor, preserve and
celebrate great collection

00:33:50.840 --> 00:33:54.580
of Armenian art there,
and I still look forward

00:33:54.580 --> 00:33:56.790
to a future collaboration
between the Walters

00:33:56.790 --> 00:33:59.010
and the Library of Congress.

00:33:59.010 --> 00:34:05.830
So, my talk today pivots around
a document of great interest

00:34:05.830 --> 00:34:09.290
for early modern Armenian
patronage and collecting.

00:34:09.290 --> 00:34:14.030
It is the will of Jota
Pohos Vallejanian.

00:34:14.030 --> 00:34:15.520
Pohos was a Zion of one

00:34:15.520 --> 00:34:17.680
of the wealthiest
Armenian merchant families

00:34:17.680 --> 00:34:20.060
of 17th century Iran.

00:34:20.060 --> 00:34:24.720
His will is dated 1062
of the Islamic calendar,

00:34:24.720 --> 00:34:28.540
which translates as
1646 of our Common Era

00:34:28.540 --> 00:34:31.740
and it was amended
seven years later.

00:34:31.740 --> 00:34:33.870
The will was originally
written in Persian,

00:34:33.870 --> 00:34:37.990
and his bequest was
translated into Armenian

00:34:37.990 --> 00:34:42.480
by the 19th century historian
Ter of Hanians, to be included

00:34:42.480 --> 00:34:45.820
in that authors "Pat
Mattoon Nor Juhaiu",

00:34:45.820 --> 00:34:48.580
or "History of New Julfa".

00:34:48.580 --> 00:34:53.090
Ter of Hanians oversaw the
archives of Sorb Amana Parchik,

00:34:53.090 --> 00:34:55.340
was a great archivist
and historian,

00:34:55.340 --> 00:34:56.640
like our dear friend LaVon,

00:34:56.640 --> 00:35:00.600
and he wrote his extraordinary
useful history published

00:35:00.600 --> 00:35:03.770
in 1880, primarily on
the basis of Persian

00:35:03.770 --> 00:35:08.950
and Armenian documents
preserved at the cathedral.

00:35:08.950 --> 00:35:12.250
Poho's will, with its
really dizzying list

00:35:12.250 --> 00:35:15.990
of palatial estates,
vineyards, shops,

00:35:15.990 --> 00:35:19.400
gold and silver tableware,
carpets, porcelain,

00:35:19.400 --> 00:35:22.090
provides a rare view of
the vast possessions owned

00:35:22.090 --> 00:35:26.040
by Armenian elites
residing in Safavid, Iran.

00:35:26.040 --> 00:35:29.170
This document excites
me as an art historian,

00:35:29.170 --> 00:35:33.420
since it offers concrete
evidence of the sizable,

00:35:33.420 --> 00:35:36.930
financial and physical
wealth of Armenian merchants,

00:35:36.930 --> 00:35:41.530
who were also major
patrons of Arts.

00:35:41.530 --> 00:35:43.830
We often reference
the enormous wealth

00:35:43.830 --> 00:35:45.310
of Armenian merchants patrons

00:35:45.310 --> 00:35:50.010
but rarely do we know the
details of their assets,

00:35:50.010 --> 00:35:53.060
which are provided
in Poho's will.

00:35:53.060 --> 00:35:56.010
In its dazzling enumeration
of properties, objects

00:35:56.010 --> 00:35:59.580
and textiles, Poho's will
offers a platform for us

00:35:59.580 --> 00:36:02.320
to discuss the amassment
of possessions both local

00:36:02.320 --> 00:36:05.740
and foreign that I believe
was key to the identity

00:36:05.740 --> 00:36:08.970
of 17th century Armenians.

00:36:08.970 --> 00:36:13.530
Surplus wealth was constantly
communicated by Polos,

00:36:13.530 --> 00:36:17.790
his family and other
Armenian resort merchants,

00:36:17.790 --> 00:36:19.190
residing as Kristyn Dime

00:36:19.190 --> 00:36:21.630
that has protected
religious minorities

00:36:21.630 --> 00:36:24.090
within the Safavieh Empire.

00:36:26.060 --> 00:36:29.030
Pohos' lists of luxury wears
and estates prompts us to think

00:36:29.030 --> 00:36:31.420
about Armenian patrons
as great collectors

00:36:31.420 --> 00:36:34.440
of the early modern
world, and it has pushed me

00:36:34.440 --> 00:36:36.160
to consider our medium
merchants,

00:36:36.160 --> 00:36:41.520
not just as devout patrons, but
also as voracious collectors.

00:36:41.520 --> 00:36:42.820
Compared with scholarship

00:36:42.820 --> 00:36:45.530
on early modern European
collecting,

00:36:45.530 --> 00:36:48.470
there has not been thorough
investigation of collecting,

00:36:48.470 --> 00:36:51.700
collections and collectors
in Iran.

00:36:51.700 --> 00:36:54.430
Within the sphere of Persian
and collecting practices,

00:36:54.430 --> 00:36:57.490
scholarship has tended
to focus on aggregations

00:36:57.490 --> 00:37:03.200
of specific media, such as
arts of the book and porcelain.

00:37:03.200 --> 00:37:07.670
Manuscripts and ceramics,
however, they were intended --

00:37:07.670 --> 00:37:10.250
they were intended to
be seen and enjoyed

00:37:10.250 --> 00:37:13.970
with other valuable objects,
resulting in "collections

00:37:13.970 --> 00:37:19.700
of collections", according to
Hoary Twatsea, or "a concert

00:37:19.700 --> 00:37:23.740
of things" as described
by Stefan Weber.

00:37:23.740 --> 00:37:27.810
Drawing upon the will of Pohos,
in association with other texts

00:37:27.810 --> 00:37:29.160
and images of the period,

00:37:29.160 --> 00:37:32.060
such as these beautiful
life-sized oil paintings were

00:37:32.060 --> 00:37:35.230
seeing in front of us, I'm
starting to explore the amassing

00:37:35.230 --> 00:37:38.530
of luxury items in association
with the accumulation

00:37:38.530 --> 00:37:41.690
of properties to understand
how various objects,

00:37:41.690 --> 00:37:46.030
such as clocks Mira's,
Italian red velvet and glass,

00:37:46.030 --> 00:37:48.940
placed in architectural
surrounds, all worked in concert

00:37:48.940 --> 00:37:52.110
to express a carefully
constructed Armenian identity,

00:37:52.110 --> 00:37:54.830
a successful merchant,
worldly collector

00:37:54.830 --> 00:37:58.000
and devout community member.

00:37:58.000 --> 00:38:00.860
So, let me begin by just
giving you a taste of the will,

00:38:00.860 --> 00:38:03.330
and as you could all see,

00:38:03.330 --> 00:38:06.500
and this is just
the will's preamble.

00:38:06.500 --> 00:38:10.190
"Before a Council, Khwaja
Polos, son of Khwaja Petros,

00:38:10.190 --> 00:38:12.850
son of Kwaja Velijanean
willfully

00:38:12.850 --> 00:38:17.070
and with complete rationality
bequeaths, to his sons Hacobjan

00:38:17.070 --> 00:38:21.480
and Hovhanjan, and their mother
Murasay, daughter of Voskan,

00:38:21.480 --> 00:38:24.480
all his possessions of which
he himself has ownership,

00:38:24.480 --> 00:38:26.520
either considerable
or inconsiderable,

00:38:26.520 --> 00:38:28.440
ready cash or possessions.

00:38:28.440 --> 00:38:31.960
That is, domestic movables,
vessels, table-cloths, rugs,

00:38:31.960 --> 00:38:35.850
carpets, thick felts, clothing,
household utensils, goldware,

00:38:35.850 --> 00:38:38.120
silverware, copperware,
enamelware" --

00:38:38.120 --> 00:38:41.120
which was probably definitely
imported, "precious stones,

00:38:41.120 --> 00:38:44.280
chinaware, livestock, purchased
slaves", and then he goes

00:38:44.280 --> 00:38:46.710
on to describe all
the four-legged beasts

00:38:46.710 --> 00:38:48.010
that he owned.

00:38:48.010 --> 00:38:52.280
"Landed property, vineyards,
houses", and the list goes on.

00:38:52.280 --> 00:38:56.030
And it concludes, "whether it be
credit, charitable capital" --

00:38:56.030 --> 00:38:59.970
and here he uses the Islamic
term "waqf", "that he invested

00:38:59.970 --> 00:39:03.780
in Julfa at Isfahan" a
place he had built and part

00:39:03.780 --> 00:39:08.880
of which he had inherited, which
are now properties in his name.

00:39:08.880 --> 00:39:12.730
So, as many of, you know,

00:39:12.730 --> 00:39:16.930
Shah Abbas forcibly deported
the Armenians from Julfa.

00:39:16.930 --> 00:39:20.910
So, Polos' amassed possessions
should be considered in light

00:39:20.910 --> 00:39:23.660
of his being third generation

00:39:23.660 --> 00:39:27.440
of the Velijanean
family in, Safavid, Iran.

00:39:27.440 --> 00:39:29.590
According to Terhov Janean's,

00:39:29.590 --> 00:39:31.690
Polos' grandfather
was from Haiajztan.

00:39:31.690 --> 00:39:35.130
"I was among those who
were originally relocated

00:39:35.130 --> 00:39:38.400
from Julfa", which you
probably saw on the map earlier.

00:39:38.400 --> 00:39:40.830
As many of you know, again,

00:39:40.830 --> 00:39:43.380
Julfa was on the
contested lands,

00:39:43.380 --> 00:39:46.000
along the Ottoman-Safavid
border.

00:39:46.000 --> 00:39:47.980
Shah Abbas the first
raised Julfa

00:39:47.980 --> 00:39:51.170
and forcibly relocated
Julfa's residents,

00:39:51.170 --> 00:39:54.210
who had already been
profiting from the sale of silk

00:39:54.210 --> 00:39:56.960
through an extensive
trade network.

00:40:00.070 --> 00:40:03.690
Due to their wealth and
mercantile connections,

00:40:03.690 --> 00:40:06.750
Shah Abbas spared
Velijanean's community,

00:40:06.750 --> 00:40:09.480
Velijanean's community,
the hardships endured

00:40:09.480 --> 00:40:13.390
by the less affluent Armenians,
and repositioned the Julfans

00:40:13.390 --> 00:40:17.830
within his empire, at Esfahan,
close to the core and very close

00:40:17.830 --> 00:40:19.720
to the commercial
center, and you have

00:40:19.720 --> 00:40:24.470
to imagine this Maydan
just buzzing with merchants

00:40:24.470 --> 00:40:27.600
and buyers in the 17th century.

00:40:29.120 --> 00:40:32.660
New Julfa was purposely
built to house the Julfans

00:40:32.660 --> 00:40:36.320
across the Zion Derude
river, the Zion Darude,

00:40:36.320 --> 00:40:38.360
the river to the
south of Isfahan.

00:40:38.360 --> 00:40:42.700
By the time Polos' father
was an active member

00:40:42.700 --> 00:40:45.370
of the New Julfa
community, the Velijanean's,

00:40:45.370 --> 00:40:47.840
along with the suburbs
other merchant families,

00:40:47.840 --> 00:40:51.200
were profiting tremendously
from selling Iranian silk

00:40:51.200 --> 00:40:53.630
across the globe,
through a network

00:40:53.630 --> 00:40:55.880
of New Julfan satellite
communities.

00:40:55.880 --> 00:40:58.320
Representatives of the
main wealthy families

00:40:58.320 --> 00:41:03.660
of Julfa were representing the
Julfan families abroad in South,

00:41:03.660 --> 00:41:06.060
Southeast Asia, East
Asia, Russia and Europe.

00:41:06.060 --> 00:41:08.570
And, of course, we have
all this information

00:41:08.570 --> 00:41:11.910
from wonderful economic
historians who are working

00:41:11.910 --> 00:41:16.540
on New Julfa at the moment,
in the past ten years.

00:41:16.540 --> 00:41:20.400
Surplus wealth went
into construction --

00:41:20.400 --> 00:41:24.290
constructing an awesome
built environment.

00:41:24.290 --> 00:41:27.990
Through a network of bridges
New Julfa became an extension

00:41:27.990 --> 00:41:30.350
of Isfahan's palace precinct.

00:41:30.350 --> 00:41:31.990
The quarters of Isfahan,

00:41:31.990 --> 00:41:36.250
inhabited by the Muslim
political elite, were connected

00:41:36.250 --> 00:41:40.130
to the most beautiful
Armenian houses of Julfa,

00:41:40.130 --> 00:41:43.660
a suburb of Isfahan through
a network of bridges,

00:41:43.660 --> 00:41:46.550
such as the one you're
seeing here.

00:41:52.060 --> 00:41:55.840
In Terhov Anians' history,
in the chapter dedicated

00:41:55.840 --> 00:42:00.220
to the Velijanians, he
immediately links Velijan with

00:42:00.220 --> 00:42:05.210
"Sorb Bethlehem" or
"Holy Bethlehem",

00:42:05.210 --> 00:42:09.340
the most stately domed church
built during the initial decades

00:42:09.340 --> 00:42:13.430
following the transportation
of the Julfans from Julfa

00:42:13.430 --> 00:42:17.100
to New Julfa, in
Juha to Nor Juha.

00:42:17.100 --> 00:42:19.160
Throughout this church,
one can find the name

00:42:19.160 --> 00:42:22.080
of Polos and his family.

00:42:22.080 --> 00:42:27.160
Petros, who founded this
glorious Church in 1628,

00:42:27.160 --> 00:42:31.080
and now we're going to
see a picture of Petros,

00:42:31.080 --> 00:42:35.060
located in the congregation
area of the church.

00:42:35.060 --> 00:42:38.230
Here we see Petros
wearing a dress analogous

00:42:38.230 --> 00:42:41.720
to the Muslim political
and economic elite.

00:42:41.720 --> 00:42:45.370
He's wearing the fur line
vest and patterned headdress,

00:42:45.370 --> 00:42:48.590
the fur probably
imported from Russia

00:42:48.590 --> 00:42:53.440
where the Armenians had very
close ties around the 1660s.

00:42:53.440 --> 00:42:56.480
And he rests his hand
on the Holy Gospel,

00:42:56.480 --> 00:43:00.020
and in the other hand, I
believe he's holding a fair mon.

00:43:00.020 --> 00:43:03.570
So, a decree issued
by the Safavid Court,

00:43:03.570 --> 00:43:07.900
which gives this Dime, this
Christian minority the ability

00:43:07.900 --> 00:43:12.270
to build a religious
structure in Isfahan.

00:43:12.270 --> 00:43:16.920
The bequest of Polos
makes frequent reference

00:43:16.920 --> 00:43:20.590
to this church, and this church
is located in the Great Square

00:43:20.590 --> 00:43:24.990
of New Julfa called
Mezmaydan, "the Great Maydan".

00:43:24.990 --> 00:43:27.430
17th century visitors, as well

00:43:27.430 --> 00:43:31.130
as our 19th century
historian Terhov Haneans,

00:43:31.130 --> 00:43:35.430
has written that Polos and
his father Petros were highly

00:43:35.430 --> 00:43:41.360
regarded for their massive
investment in this great square,

00:43:41.360 --> 00:43:45.530
which was really the
commercial heart of the suburb.

00:43:45.530 --> 00:43:48.700
And here I quote Terhov
Hanians who writes,

00:43:48.700 --> 00:43:53.390
"especially its homes, its
beautifully laid out shops

00:43:53.390 --> 00:43:55.970
and its magnificent Church".

00:43:58.240 --> 00:44:01.930
I'd like to pause on the overall
effect of Bethlehem Church,

00:44:01.930 --> 00:44:04.450
which is decorated with
European-style murals,

00:44:04.450 --> 00:44:07.650
and here Bethlehem is actually
the first church to be decorated

00:44:07.650 --> 00:44:10.130
with these Europeanized
murals so, we have to think

00:44:10.130 --> 00:44:12.850
of the Velijanean
family as really ushering

00:44:12.850 --> 00:44:18.420
in this new mode referred to
as "ferein ushazi" in Isfahan.

00:44:18.420 --> 00:44:21.500
So, one, as we all know at this
point, many of us have worked

00:44:21.500 --> 00:44:25.900
on this, the wall paintings
in the church are based

00:44:25.900 --> 00:44:29.780
on prints -- will
ultimately derive from prints,

00:44:29.780 --> 00:44:32.960
"Evangelicae Historiae
Magnus", and this was printed

00:44:32.960 --> 00:44:35.520
in the late 16th
century and Antwerp

00:44:35.520 --> 00:44:38.250
and it had many different
iterations throughout the

00:44:38.250 --> 00:44:39.870
17th century.

00:44:39.870 --> 00:44:42.450
But we really have to
see, we've been focusing

00:44:42.450 --> 00:44:44.070
on these wall paintings,

00:44:44.070 --> 00:44:49.230
but we have to see the
entire structure in concert.

00:44:49.230 --> 00:44:54.030
So, we have to look at the
portrait, the paintings,

00:44:54.030 --> 00:44:56.860
the gilded stucco
and the cobble tiles

00:44:56.860 --> 00:45:00.370
with yellow inscriptions just
really pronouncing the name

00:45:00.370 --> 00:45:03.330
of Petros, Polos
and their family.

00:45:03.330 --> 00:45:05.920
And we have to imagine
this building covered

00:45:05.920 --> 00:45:10.740
in beautiful silk carpets,
embroidered with metallic thread

00:45:10.740 --> 00:45:15.120
and with Pope's -- with
Popes, sorry about that,

00:45:15.120 --> 00:45:17.870
that was a bad mistake.

00:45:17.870 --> 00:45:20.280
But [laughter] with
priests processing

00:45:20.280 --> 00:45:23.560
in such glorious copes
as the one you see here,

00:45:23.560 --> 00:45:25.800
which actually the members

00:45:25.800 --> 00:45:29.870
of Victorian Albert Museum have
found an Armenian inscription

00:45:29.870 --> 00:45:32.650
in this cloak.

00:45:32.650 --> 00:45:34.240
Adjacent to this church --

00:45:34.240 --> 00:45:36.520
so, we have to think
of entering this church

00:45:36.520 --> 00:45:38.120
as a sensory experience,

00:45:38.120 --> 00:45:42.820
and when the visitor leaves
the church, there is a plethora

00:45:42.820 --> 00:45:45.740
of shops that are
also associated

00:45:45.740 --> 00:45:49.950
with Polos and his family.

00:45:49.950 --> 00:45:54.440
The French traveler Jean
Baptiste Tavernier writes,

00:45:54.440 --> 00:45:58.300
"the beautiful square in which
the market is held is entirely

00:45:58.300 --> 00:46:01.720
surrounded by shops,
it's another of the works

00:46:01.720 --> 00:46:06.950
for which the public is beholden
to Petros, Polos' father,

00:46:06.950 --> 00:46:11.700
and which render his memory
famous among the Armenians".

00:46:11.700 --> 00:46:15.900
The will also continue to
list all the other shops,

00:46:15.900 --> 00:46:20.930
not just in New Julfa but
in other suburbs of Isfahan.

00:46:26.060 --> 00:46:28.900
Well, the request
statement does not say.

00:46:28.900 --> 00:46:31.160
We may assume that the
various shops owned

00:46:31.160 --> 00:46:36.530
by Polos sold both
local and foreign goods.

00:46:36.530 --> 00:46:39.470
Although the Safavid Court
unilaterally commissioned

00:46:39.470 --> 00:46:42.390
European merchants to obtain
foreign items for them,

00:46:42.390 --> 00:46:45.480
it was the Armenians who
really had the lion's share

00:46:45.480 --> 00:46:47.840
of the market as
importers of European

00:46:47.840 --> 00:46:50.840
and Russian luxury wares.

00:46:50.840 --> 00:46:52.330
Importation of foreign goods

00:46:52.330 --> 00:46:55.600
by Armenian merchants is
really well documented,

00:46:55.600 --> 00:46:57.750
and we see reference to this

00:46:57.750 --> 00:47:01.300
in these two oil
paintings in front of us.

00:47:01.300 --> 00:47:05.690
Venetian glass, Italian
red velvet,

00:47:05.690 --> 00:47:09.840
enamelware, European clocks.

00:47:09.840 --> 00:47:14.720
Reading through the latter part
of the will, one is astounded

00:47:14.720 --> 00:47:18.430
by the sheer number of
properties owned by Polos.

00:47:18.430 --> 00:47:21.640
The document lists houses in
New Julfa and, as I mentioned,

00:47:21.640 --> 00:47:24.390
other suburbs of Isfahan.

00:47:24.390 --> 00:47:30.020
They were built close to the
church and close to the shops,

00:47:30.020 --> 00:47:31.320
but we also have to think

00:47:31.320 --> 00:47:34.300
about all these houses
being built next

00:47:34.300 --> 00:47:37.820
to other important patrons of
New Julfa, such as the family

00:47:37.820 --> 00:47:41.310
of Tsar Fras and the
family of Abbatik.

00:47:41.310 --> 00:47:45.220
Abbatik -- the reference to
Abbatik may be the individual

00:47:45.220 --> 00:47:50.980
who was part of the commission
of the cathedral, Amana Parkich.

00:47:50.980 --> 00:47:54.440
Clearly ownership of property
was a good investment.

00:47:54.440 --> 00:47:57.040
Traditionally land
ownership in the Middle East

00:47:57.040 --> 00:47:59.930
in Europe was the
basis of wealth.

00:47:59.930 --> 00:48:03.220
Houses were assets that
could be used or bequeathed

00:48:03.220 --> 00:48:06.020
by family members
and there is evidence

00:48:06.020 --> 00:48:10.150
that the domestic properties
were even rented out.

00:48:10.150 --> 00:48:12.130
Aside from the economic
benefits, however,

00:48:12.130 --> 00:48:14.570
I'd like to point out
the sociological aspect

00:48:14.570 --> 00:48:16.910
to the amassment of properties.

00:48:16.910 --> 00:48:18.980
And for comparison we
could look to the Jews

00:48:18.980 --> 00:48:21.990
of the Ottoman Empire.

00:48:21.990 --> 00:48:25.770
New Julfa, merchants who were
also "outsiders", quote-unquote,

00:48:25.770 --> 00:48:27.980
as a relocated Dimmi community,

00:48:27.980 --> 00:48:31.570
desire to show their communal
investment and their ties,

00:48:31.570 --> 00:48:35.610
their location to their
built environment.

00:48:35.610 --> 00:48:39.270
Within these spaces, these
public and private spaces,

00:48:39.270 --> 00:48:43.800
affluent Armenian families like
the Velijaneans, received --

00:48:43.800 --> 00:48:47.190
they welcomed into their
house Armenian, European,

00:48:47.190 --> 00:48:50.930
Russian merchants, as well as
members of foreign embassies,

00:48:50.930 --> 00:48:53.800
including ambassadors.

00:48:53.800 --> 00:48:57.840
This is especially true
of the public areas

00:48:57.840 --> 00:49:03.160
of palatial estates, and 17th
century sources are replete

00:49:03.160 --> 00:49:08.100
with references to visits on
behalf of the Safavids Court.

00:49:08.100 --> 00:49:11.620
We know through the good
work of Cara Pettean

00:49:11.620 --> 00:49:15.670
that the Velijaneans
owned a house, a mansion,

00:49:15.670 --> 00:49:18.220
that in one room was decorated
with the eight wonders

00:49:18.220 --> 00:49:21.090
of the world so, that's
an additional one.

00:49:21.090 --> 00:49:25.380
And much work needs to be done
on interpreting why they felt

00:49:25.380 --> 00:49:28.220
that these eight
wonders were important.

00:49:28.220 --> 00:49:33.060
They probably derived from
Hemskirk, a printed source.

00:49:33.060 --> 00:49:35.780
And also we could
assume that in the houses

00:49:35.780 --> 00:49:40.270
of the Velijaneans they
had life-size oil paintings

00:49:40.270 --> 00:49:42.480
such as the ones were
seeing before us.

00:49:42.480 --> 00:49:45.670
A number of these survived
and they're seen in situ

00:49:45.670 --> 00:49:48.440
and the few mansions
of the Armenians

00:49:48.440 --> 00:49:51.720
that survived in
New Julfa today.

00:49:51.720 --> 00:49:54.130
What are we looking at?

00:49:54.130 --> 00:49:56.360
So, here we're looking
at single figures

00:49:56.360 --> 00:50:00.040
in these fantastic
European-style interiors.

00:50:00.040 --> 00:50:05.740
The columns are decorated
with Pucci, the ballast rod

00:50:05.740 --> 00:50:10.210
and the claw leg-type table
are all service backdrops

00:50:10.210 --> 00:50:13.980
and basically they're riffing
off of royal portraiture

00:50:13.980 --> 00:50:17.360
that is being circulated
throughout Iran,

00:50:17.360 --> 00:50:20.540
and here we see Louis
XIII and Anne of Austria.

00:50:20.540 --> 00:50:24.510
And on the right hand side --

00:50:24.510 --> 00:50:28.290
no, yes, on your left
hand side we see an urn

00:50:28.290 --> 00:50:31.390
that is probably drawn
from a printed source.

00:50:31.390 --> 00:50:35.270
They're really fantastical,
imagined objects

00:50:35.270 --> 00:50:40.520
that European artists
are circulating in Iran.

00:50:40.520 --> 00:50:43.730
And what -- these
are not individuals

00:50:43.730 --> 00:50:45.030
that are being depicted --

00:50:45.030 --> 00:50:48.540
they are types, and they're what
type they are is communicated

00:50:48.540 --> 00:50:54.900
by the details of
dress and head wear.

00:50:54.900 --> 00:51:00.440
And Cornelius Debruyne documents
one of the elite Armenian women,

00:51:00.440 --> 00:51:03.440
and just look closely -- and
I don't need to describe it

00:51:03.440 --> 00:51:07.040
for you, but if you look
at her specific head wear

00:51:07.040 --> 00:51:12.900
and gold coins hanging down
from it, it was created

00:51:12.900 --> 00:51:15.080
to make a great impression.

00:51:15.080 --> 00:51:20.580
So, the luxury goods depicted,

00:51:20.580 --> 00:51:22.830
they speak to both
the realities,

00:51:22.830 --> 00:51:27.830
as well as the aspirations of
Armenian mercantile elites.

00:51:27.830 --> 00:51:30.280
The wine tape -- the wine
decanter on the table

00:51:30.280 --> 00:51:33.390
on the long stem glass,
they've been identified

00:51:33.390 --> 00:51:37.020
as venetian manufacture and
the stopper of the decanter

00:51:37.020 --> 00:51:40.510
in the form of the three
eagle head is believed

00:51:40.510 --> 00:51:43.090
to be a Russian design.

00:51:43.090 --> 00:51:47.660
And I already mentioned her
coat, red velvet, is a reference

00:51:47.660 --> 00:51:51.960
to Italian manufacturer
and we also find references

00:51:51.960 --> 00:51:57.740
to Italian red velvet in
Persian sources of the period.

00:51:57.740 --> 00:52:03.250
So, let's just recall the
list in Polos' request.

00:52:03.250 --> 00:52:07.180
The silverware, the china, the
carpets, the enamels and more.

00:52:07.180 --> 00:52:08.480
Polos like other members

00:52:08.480 --> 00:52:11.530
of the Safavid elite amassed
a significant collection

00:52:11.530 --> 00:52:13.470
of luxury items.

00:52:13.470 --> 00:52:16.560
The desire to assemble
diverse objects

00:52:16.560 --> 00:52:20.710
in this massive quantity, which
is enumerated in this will,

00:52:20.710 --> 00:52:24.210
was shared by the Safavid Court
and by other Armenian families.

00:52:24.210 --> 00:52:27.600
And these individuals
were all mutually invested

00:52:27.600 --> 00:52:31.320
in imparting this image
of really unlimited wealth

00:52:31.320 --> 00:52:36.310
and opulence, in a
17th century context.

00:52:36.310 --> 00:52:38.380
The emphasis is usually
on foreign goods,

00:52:38.380 --> 00:52:42.380
and there was an
investment, actually,

00:52:42.380 --> 00:52:44.620
to maintain the foreign
nature of goods

00:52:44.620 --> 00:52:47.950
by not making certain
things like enamels locally,

00:52:47.950 --> 00:52:51.310
but importing them
abroad, from abroad.

00:52:51.310 --> 00:52:54.830
And that ability to own
foreign items became a privilege

00:52:54.830 --> 00:52:57.290
of the court and the Armenians.

00:52:57.290 --> 00:53:00.580
It became a sign of class
and social differentiation.

00:53:00.580 --> 00:53:07.710
I believe that the amassment
of luxury wares and domiciles

00:53:07.710 --> 00:53:10.270
on behalf of the Armenians
like Polos was driven

00:53:10.270 --> 00:53:14.550
by this common impulse, a desire
to maintain a privileged social

00:53:14.550 --> 00:53:18.630
and economic standing
in the Safavid Empire.

00:53:18.630 --> 00:53:22.080
Objects and architecture worked
in concert as an expression

00:53:22.080 --> 00:53:24.140
of lifestyle, taste
and the knowledge

00:53:24.140 --> 00:53:27.970
of worlds well beyond
Safavid, Iran.

00:53:27.970 --> 00:53:31.160
According to Dimmi Law, New
Julfa's Armenians were to be

00:53:31.160 --> 00:53:33.600
of lower social standing
and political stratum

00:53:33.600 --> 00:53:35.640
than their Muslim peers.

00:53:35.640 --> 00:53:39.470
Their ready access of cash,
however, allowed these merchants

00:53:39.470 --> 00:53:42.370
to build and buy beautiful
homes and wonderful things

00:53:42.370 --> 00:53:44.500
to decorate them with.

00:53:44.500 --> 00:53:48.020
This conspicuous consumption
signaled membership and thus off

00:53:48.020 --> 00:53:51.200
of it upper class,
including an association

00:53:51.200 --> 00:53:53.670
with the Persian court.

00:53:53.670 --> 00:53:57.240
Polos' is request -- the
quest gives an immediate

00:53:57.240 --> 00:54:01.580
and firsthand description
of the numerous houses

00:54:01.580 --> 00:54:06.400
and the luxury items that
were used to furnish them.

00:54:06.400 --> 00:54:10.260
There must be more documents
like this and I'm looking

00:54:10.260 --> 00:54:16.100
to my colleagues in the field to
work on them and to publish them

00:54:16.100 --> 00:54:19.260
because only then will we
actually know the enormous

00:54:19.260 --> 00:54:22.910
wealth that these
Armenians of New Julfa had,

00:54:22.910 --> 00:54:26.610
and we need to analyze exactly
what objects are coming in

00:54:26.610 --> 00:54:30.590
and how foreign and local
goods are working together

00:54:30.590 --> 00:54:33.920
in the houses of New
Julfa, which still remain

00:54:33.920 --> 00:54:35.440
to be documented in full.

00:54:35.440 --> 00:54:37.510
I thank you for your attention

00:54:37.510 --> 00:54:44.270
[ Applause ]

00:54:44.270 --> 00:54:48.490
&gt;&gt; All right, thanks
Jamie Landau.

00:54:48.490 --> 00:54:52.660
This, both Dr. Evans and Dr.
Landau's paper reminds me

00:54:52.660 --> 00:54:57.940
of another point that needs to
be made, which is the influence

00:54:57.940 --> 00:55:01.400
of Armenia on its neighbors and
the influence of the neighbors

00:55:01.400 --> 00:55:05.600
on Armenia, both of those papers
give wonderful examples of that.

00:55:05.600 --> 00:55:09.760
And also the fact that
everyone you are listening

00:55:09.760 --> 00:55:15.660
to today is an active
researcher in archives and user

00:55:15.660 --> 00:55:18.090
of digital collections,
and that's another point

00:55:18.090 --> 00:55:20.290
to be made by their papers.

00:55:20.290 --> 00:55:26.450
And that also brings me to a
dear friend, a colleague of mine

00:55:26.450 --> 00:55:31.350
at Columbia studied under
Nina Garzion, who will speak

00:55:31.350 --> 00:55:34.660
on some beloved manuscripts
of ours here in the Library

00:55:34.660 --> 00:55:36.020
of Congress and elsewhere.

00:55:36.020 --> 00:55:39.680
I speak of Sylvie
Merion, who is at --

00:55:39.680 --> 00:55:43.640
and I have got to get
this absolutely correct,

00:55:43.640 --> 00:55:51.050
is at the Pierpont
Morgan Museum and --

00:55:51.050 --> 00:55:53.240
&gt;&gt; Morgan Library and Museum.

00:55:53.240 --> 00:55:54.540
&gt;&gt; Library and Museum.

00:55:54.540 --> 00:55:58.360
And is an expert on all
things related to Book Arts,

00:55:58.360 --> 00:56:00.730
manuscript arts and
illuminations,

00:56:00.730 --> 00:56:04.480
and today she will speak to
us on the eclectic nature

00:56:04.480 --> 00:56:09.510
of late Armenian manuscripts
from Constantinople, Dr. Merion.

00:56:09.510 --> 00:56:14.740
